<div id="banner">
	<h1>Arrgh, pirates.</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>I&#8217;ve often complained to folks about their use of the term &#8220;pirate&#8221; to mean &#8220;share&#8221;. When folks complain about pirated movies, do they really mean to imply that sharing movies with someone is the moral equivalent of attacking a ship?<p /><p />However, as the word gains more prevalence, I can&#8217;t help but wonder if the negative connotations will wear off &#8212; we&#8217;re even seeing it <a href="http://www.dictionary.com/cgi-bin/dict.pl?term=pirate">in the dictionary</a>as &#8220;To make use of or reproduce (another&#8217;s work) without authorization&#8221;. <em>Hey Johnny, I&#8217;ve got a pirated copy of Shakespeare for you!</em> Why just the other day my math teacher mentioned that she had &#8220;pirated&#8221; some of the examples she was writing on the board from the textbook.</p>

<p class="posted">posted February 04, 2002 07:25 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_technology">Technology</a>)  <a href="000158" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

